an, battles a corruption scandal which has seen a stream of anonymous postings purportedly revealing government wrongdoing appear on the social media platform in recent weeks.</p><p>The blockage triggered local and international criticism days ahead of critical elections.</p><p>Turkey's bar association described the move as an \"arbitrary decision\" that was against the law and launched an appeal at the Ankara administrative court. Its earlier attempt to challenge the blockage failed when a court in Istanbul said there was no legal ruling for it to overturn.</p><p>Friday's blockage came hours after Erdoğan vowed on the campaign trail to get rid of Twitter. He said late on Tuesday that the network \"was threatening national security\" and that it had refused to co-operate with the Turkish authorities.</p><p>Erdoğan claimed audio postings were part of a plot contrived by his political enemies to unseat him ahead of the nationwide local elections on Sunday, which are widely being seen as a referendum on his 11-year rule.</p><p>Reuters has not been able to verify the authenticity of the recordings.</p><p>Telecoms regulators have said their blockage was based on four court orders and was imposed after complaints from citizens that Twitter was violating privacy.</p>","headline":"Turkish court upholds appeal against ban on Twitter","trailText":"Block imposed by Turkey's telecoms authority ahead of elections has not yet been removed <br />","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/26/1395835700771/Turkish-Prime-Minister-Re-006.jpg","wordcount":"240","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-29T12:17:36Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/mar/26/turkish-court-upholds-appeal-end-block-twitter-recep-tayyip-erdogan","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/technology/2014/mar/26/turkish-court-upholds-appeal-end-block-twitter-recep-tayyip-erdogan","tags":[{"id":"technology/twitter","webTitle":"Twitter","t