e.</p><p>Now, however, ISPs have begun blocking the IP addresses used by Twitter themselves, according to an analysis carried out by internet monitoring firm Renesys. And a Turkish government webpage confirmed the block, citing court orders.</p><p>The move represents an escalation in the battle between the Erdogan regime and the social media network. His attempts to block the site on Thursday were derided by Turkish President Abdullah Gül, who flouted it himself.</p><p>In a series of messages posted on Twitter, he said: \"The shutdown of an entire social platform is unacceptable. Besides, as I have said many times before, it is technically impossible to close down communication technologies like Twitter entirely. I hope this measure will not last long.\"</p><p>While more difficult, it is still technically possible to get around the ban if users can make it appear that they are accessing Twitter from outside Turkey. Twitter refused to comment, but it is understood to be aware of the development.</p>","headline":"Turkey steps up bid to block Twitter after users flout ban","trailText":"Move follows threats from Turkish prime minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan that he would 'root out' the social media network","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/23/1395617745576/Turkish-Prime-Minister-Re-003.jpg","wordcount":"279","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-26T23:38:06Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/23/turkey-twitter-ban","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/2014/mar/23/turkey-twitter-ban","tags":[{"id":"world/turkey","webTitle":"Turkey","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/turkey","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/turkey","references":[]},{"id":"world/world","webTitle":"World news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/world","a